<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-402-690  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 402 690.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 30 1990 v12 n18 p40(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Interconnectivity for the '90s: linking LANs, WANs, and MANs.andO;(local area networks, wide area networks and metropolitan areanetworks) (Tech Street) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gantz, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The main trend in networking during the 1990s will involve thenetworking of networks and the growth of metropolitan areanetworks.andP;  The growth of MANs, which will bridge the gap betweenlocal area networks (LANs) and wide area networks (WANs), will bedriven by fiber optic technology.andP;  The bandwidth and data transferrates made possible by fiber optics will result in networks thatcan operate at 90Mbps by 1994.andP;  The growth of MANs will also befacilitated by the spread of the IEEE 802.6 protocol standard, atoken ring passing access technology.andP;  Telephone companies are inline to provide switching services for MANs, with the first to beknown Switched Multimegabit Data Service (SMDS).andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ArchitectureTrendsLocal Area NetworksWide Area NetworksMetropolitan Area NetworksFiber OpticsNetwork ManagementCommunications Technology.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>